scene "intro" {
    index: "a1";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "trig_foundations";
    title: "1. Introduction to Trigonometric Ratios";
    body: """
## Welcome to the Complete Trigonometric Ratios Masterclass

This lesson covers **all 30+ trigonometric formulas** you will ever need — from basic definitions to advanced product-to-sum conversions.

### What You Will Master

- **6 Basic Ratios** (sin, cos, tan, csc, sec, cot)
- **3 Reciprocal Identities**
- **3 Pythagorean Identities**
- **2 Quotient Identities**
- **6 Co-function Identities**
- **3 Even-Odd Identities**
- **6 Sum & Difference Formulas**
- **3 Double Angle Formulas**
- **3 Half Angle Formulas**
- **4 Product-to-Sum Formulas**
- **4 Sum-to-Product Formulas**
- **3 Triple Angle Formulas**
- **Law of Sines & Law of Cosines**
> **That's 48 formulas total.** By the end, you'll recognize patterns, derive them from memory, and solve MCQs in under 30 seconds.

### How This Lesson Works

Each module teaches a group of related formulas, followed by **interactive simulations** and **adaptive quizzes**. If you struggle, you'll be looped back for review. If you excel, you'll advance to harder problems.

Let's begin with the **Unit Circle** — the foundation of everything.
""";
}

scene "unit_circle_intro" {
    index: "a2";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "trig_foundations";
    title: "2. The Unit Circle — Your Best Friend";
    body: """
## The Unit Circle

The **unit circle** is a circle of radius 1 centered at the origin. For any angle \\(\\theta\\), the point on the circle is:

\\[(x, y) = (\\cos\\theta, \\sin\\theta)\\]

This single fact gives birth to **every** trigonometric identity.

### Why Radius = 1 Matters

Since \\(x^2 + y^2 = r^2\\) and \\(r = 1\\):

\\[\\cos^2\\theta + \\sin^2\\theta = 1\\]

That's your first Pythagorean identity — derived in one line!

### Key Angles to Memorize

| Angle | 0° | 30° | 45° | 60° | 90° |
|-------|-----|------|------|------|------|
| sin   | 0   | 1/2  | √2/2 | √3/2 | 1    |
| cos   | 1   | √3/2 | √2/2 | 1/2  | 0    |
| tan   | 0   | 1/√3 | 1    | √3   | undef|

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** Memorize this table. 80% of MCQs use these angles. If you see sin 30° in a problem, you should instantly think "1/2" without calculating.
""";
}

scene "unit_circle_sim" {
    index: "a3";
    concept: "trig_foundations";
    title: "Interactive Unit Circle";
    simulation "unit_circle" {
        description: "Drag the point around the unit circle to see how sin, cos, and tan change in real time.";        raw: """
<div style="display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:20px;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-family:sans-serif;">
  <canvas id="ucCanvas" width="400" height="400" style="border:1px solid #ccc;border-radius:8px;background:#1a1a2e;"></canvas>
  <div id="ucInfo" style="min-width:200px;font-size:15px;line-height:2;color:#e0e0e0;background:#16213e;padding:16px;border-radius:8px;">
    <div>Angle: <strong id="ucAngle">45°</strong></div>
    <div>sin θ = <strong id="ucSin" style="color:#ff6b6b;">0.707</strong></div>
    <div>cos θ = <strong id="ucCos" style="color:#4ecdc4;">0.707</strong></div>
    <div>tan θ = <strong id="ucTan" style="color:#ffe66d;">1.000</strong></div>
    <div style="margin-top:12px;font-size:12px;color:#888;">Click & drag on the circle</div>
  </div>
</div>
<script>
(function(){
  const c=document.getElementById('ucCanvas'),ctx=c.getContext('2d');
  const W=400,H=400,cx=W/2,cy=H/2,R=150;
  let angle=Math.PI/4,dragging=false;
  function draw(){
    ctx.clearRect(0,0,W,H);
    ctx.strokeStyle='#333';ctx.lineWidth=1;
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.moveTo(0,cy);ctx.lineTo(W,cy);ctx.stroke();
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.moveTo(cx,0);ctx.lineTo(cx,H);ctx.stroke();
    ctx.strokeStyle='#4ecdc4';ctx.lineWidth=2;
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.arc(cx,cy,R,0,2*Math.PI);ctx.stroke();
    const px=cx+R*Math.cos(angle),py=cy-R*Math.sin(angle);
    ctx.strokeStyle='#4ecdc4';ctx.lineWidth=2;
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.moveTo(cx,cy);ctx.lineTo(px,cy);ctx.stroke();
    ctx.strokeStyle='#ff6b6b';ctx.lineWidth=2;
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.moveTo(px,cy);ctx.lineTo(px,py);ctx.stroke();
    ctx.strokeStyle='#ffe66d';ctx.lineWidth=1.5;ctx.setLineDash([4,4]);
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.moveTo(cx,cy);ctx.lineTo(px,py);ctx.stroke();
    ctx.setLineDash([]);
    ctx.fillStyle='#ff6b6b';ctx.beginPath();ctx.arc(px,py,6,0,2*Math.PI);ctx.fill();
    ctx.strokeStyle='#fff';ctx.lineWidth=1;ctx.beginPath();ctx.arc(cx,cy,R,0,-angle,true);ctx.stroke();
    document.getElementById('ucAngle').textContent=(angle*180/Math.PI).toFixed(1)+'°';
    document.getElementById('ucSin').textContent=Math.sin(angle).toFixed(3);
    document.getElementById('ucCos').textContent=Math.cos(angle).toFixed(3);
    const cosV=Math.cos(angle);
    document.getElementById('ucTan').textContent=Math.abs(cosV)<0.01?'undefined':Math.tan(angle).toFixed(3);
  }
  function getAngle(e){
    const rect=c.getBoundingClientRect();
    const x=(e.clientX||e.touches[0].clientX)-rect.left-cx;
    const y=-((e.clientY||e.touches[0].clientY)-rect.top-cy);
    angle=Math.atan2(y,x);if(angle<0)angle+=2*Math.PI;
    draw();
  }
  c.addEventListener('mousedown',()=>{dragging=true;});
  c.addEventListener('mousemove',(e)=>{if(dragging)getAngle(e);});
  c.addEventListener('mouseup',()=>{dragging=false;});
  c.addEventListener('mouseleave',()=>{dragging=false;});  c.addEventListener('touchstart',(e)=>{dragging=true;getAngle(e);});
  c.addEventListener('touchmove',(e)=>{if(dragging)getAngle(e);});
  c.addEventListener('touchend',()=>{dragging=false;});
  draw();
})();
</script>
""";
    }
}

