scene "basic_ratios" {
    index: "a4";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "basic_ratios";
    title: "3. The 6 Basic Trig Ratios";
    body: """
## Formulas 1–6: Basic Definitions

In a right triangle with angle \\(\\theta\\), opposite side \\(o\\), adjacent side \\(a\\), and hypotenuse \\(h\\):

### Primary Ratios

\\[\\sin\\theta = \\frac{o}{h} \\quad \\text{(Formula 1)}\\]

\\[\\cos\\theta = \\frac{a}{h} \\quad \\text{(Formula 2)}\\]

\\[\\tan\\theta = \\frac{o}{a} \\quad \\text{(Formula 3)}\\]

### Reciprocal Ratios

\\[\\csc\\theta = \\frac{h}{o} = \\frac{1}{\\sin\\theta} \\quad \\text{(Formula 4)}\\]

\\[\\sec\\theta = \\frac{h}{a} = \\frac{1}{\\cos\\theta} \\quad \\text{(Formula 5)}\\]

\\[\\cot\\theta = \\frac{a}{o} = \\frac{1}{\\tan\\theta} \\quad \\text{(Formula 6)}\\]

### Mnemonic: SOH-CAH-TOA

- **S**in = **O**pposite / **H**ypotenuse
- **C**os = **A**djacent / **H**ypotenuse
- **T**an = **O**pposite / **A**djacent

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** If you see csc, sec, or cot in an MCQ, **immediately convert** to sin, cos, or tan. This eliminates confusion and lets you work with only 3 functions.
""";
}
scene "reciprocal_identities" {
    index: "a5";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "reciprocal_identities";
    title: "4. Reciprocal Identities (Formulas 7–9)";
    body: """
## Formulas 7–9: Reciprocal Identities

These follow directly from the definitions:

\\[\\sin\\theta = \\frac{1}{\\csc\\theta} \\quad \\text{(Formula 7)}\\]

\\[\\cos\\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sec\\theta} \\quad \\text{(Formula 8)}\\]

\\[\\tan\\theta = \\frac{1}{\\cot\\theta} \\quad \\text{(Formula 9)}\\]

### Why These Matter in MCQs

**Example:** Simplify \\(\\csc\\theta \\cdot \\sin\\theta\\)

Since \\(\\csc\\theta = 1/\\sin\\theta\\), the product is simply **1**.

**Example:** If \\(\\sec\\theta = 5/3\\), find \\(\\cos\\theta\\).

\\(\\cos\\theta = 1/\\sec\\theta = 3/5\\). Done in 5 seconds.

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** Reciprocal pairs always multiply to 1:
> - \\(\\sin\\theta \\cdot \\csc\\theta = 1\\)
> - \\(\\cos\\theta \\cdot \\sec\\theta = 1\\)
> - \\(\\tan\\theta \\cdot \\cot\\theta = 1\\)
>
> Spot these pairs instantly in MCQ options to eliminate wrong answers.
""";
}

scene "quiz_basic_reciprocal" {
    index: "a6";
    concept: "basic_ratios";
    title: "Quiz: Basic Ratios & Reciprocals";

    mcq "q_basic1" {
        Q: "If sin θ = 3/5, what is csc θ?";
        A: "b";
        O: a) "3/5", b) "5/3", c) "4/5", d) "5/4";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Correct! csc θ = 1/sin θ = 5/3. Instant reciprocal!";
            goto "q_basic2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Remember: csc θ is simply 1/sin θ. Flip the fraction!";            @loopback "reciprocal_identities" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_basic2" {
        Q: "In a right triangle, if the opposite side is 4 and the hypotenuse is 5, what is cos θ?";
        A: "c";
        O: a) "4/5", b) "4/3", c) "3/5", d) "5/4";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Right! First find adjacent = √(25-16) = 3, then cos θ = 3/5.";
            goto "q_basic3";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Use Pythagorean theorem: adj = √(5²-4²) = 3. Then cos = adj/hyp = 3/5.";
            @loopback "basic_ratios" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_basic3" {
        Q: "What is tan θ × cot θ equal to?";
        A: "a";
        O: a) "1", b) "0", c) "sin θ", d) "sec²θ";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Perfect! They are reciprocals, so the product is always 1.";
            goto "pythagorean_identities";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Since cot θ = 1到的1/tan θ, their product is always 1.";
            @loopback "reciprocal_identities" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 3: PYTHAGOREAN IDENTITIES (Formulas 10-12)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "pythagorean_identities" {
    index: "a7";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "pythagorean";
    title: "5. Pythagorean Identities (Formulas 10–12)";
    body: """
## The Three Pythagorean Identities
These are the **most frequently tested** identities in every exam.

### Identity 1 (The Mother Identity) — Formula 10

\\[\\sin^2\\theta + \\cos^2\\theta = 1\\]

**Derived from:** The unit circle equation \\(x^2 + y^2 = 1\\).

### Identity 2 — Formula 11

Divide Identity 1 by \\(\\cos^2\\theta\\):

\\[\\frac{\\sin^2\\theta}{\\cos^2\\theta} + \\frac{\\cos^2\\theta}{\\cos^2\\theta} = \\frac{1}{\\cos^2\\theta}\\]

\\[\\tan^2\\theta + 1 = \\sec^2\\theta\\]

### Identity 3 — Formula 12

Divide Identity 1 by \\(\\sin^2\\theta\\):

\\[1 + \\cot^2\\theta = \\csc^2\\theta\\]

### Useful Rearrangements

From Formula 10:
- \\(\\sin^2\\theta = 1 - \\cos^2\\theta\\)
- \\(\\cos^2\\theta = 1 - \\sin^2\\theta\\)
- \\(\\sin\\theta = \\pm\\sqrt{1 - \\cos^2\\theta}\\)

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** Whenever you see \\(\\sin^2\\theta + \\cos^2\\theta\\) anywhere in an expression — even buried inside a larger problem — **replace it with 1 immediately**. This simplification appears in roughly 40% of trig MCQs.

> **🏎️ Speed Tip #2:** If you see \\(\\sec^2\\theta - \\tan^2\\theta\\), the answer is **1**. If you see \\(\\csc^2\\theta - \\cot^2\\theta\\), the answer is also **1**. These are rearranged Pythagorean identities and appear as "trick" options in MCQs.
""";
}

scene "pythagorean_sim" {
    index: "a8";
    concept: "pythagorean";
    title: "Interactive: Pythagorean Identity Visualizer";
    simulation "pyth_sim" {
        description: "Watch sin²θ + cos²θ always equal 1 as you change the angle.";
        raw: """
<div style="font-family:sans-serif;background:#0f0f23;color:#e0e0e0;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;text-align:center;">
  <h3 style="color:#4ecdc4;">sin²θ + cos²θ = ?</h3>
  <input type="range" id="pythSlider" min="0" max="360" value="45" style="width:80%;margin:15px 0;">
  <div style="font-size:20px;margin:10px 0;">
    θ = <span id="pythAngle">45</span>°
  </div>
  <div style="display:flex;justify-content:center;gap:30px;margin:15px 0;flex-wrap:wrap;">    <div style="background:#1a1a3e;padding:12px 20px;border-radius:8px;">
      <span style="color:#ff6b6b;">sin²θ</span> = <strong id="pythSin2">0.500</strong>
    </div>
    <div style="background:#1a1a3e;padding:12px 20px;border-radius:8px;">
      <span style="color:#4ecdc4;">cos²θ</span> = <strong id="pythCos2">0.500</strong>
    </div>
    <div style="background:#1a1a3e;padding:12px 20px;border-radius:8px;border:2px solid #ffe66d;">
      <span style="color:#ffe66d;">Sum</span> = <strong id="pythSum">1.000</strong>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:10px;">
    <div style="display:inline-block;width:200px;height:20px;background:#333;border-radius:10px;overflow:hidden;">
      <div id="pythBar1" style="height:100%;background:#ff6b6b;float:left;width:50%;transition:width 0.2s;"></div>
      <div id="pythBar2" style="height:100%;background:#4ecdc4;float:left;width:50%;transition:width 0.2s;"></div>
    </div>
    <div style="font-size:11px;color:#888;margin-top:5px;">Bar always fills exactly to 1.0</div>
  </div>
</div>
<script>
(function(){
  const sl=document.getElementById('pythSlider');
  function update(){
    const deg=parseFloat(sl.value);
    const rad=deg*Math.PI/180;
    const s2=Math.sin(rad)**2, c2=Math.cos(rad)**2;
    document.getElementById('pythAngle').textContent=deg;
    document.getElementById('pythSin2').textContent=s2.toFixed(4);
    document.getElementById('pythCos2').textContent=c2.toFixed(4);
    document.getElementById('pythSum').textContent=(s2+c2).toFixed(4);
    document.getElementById('pythBar1').style.width=(s2*100)+'%';
    document.getElementById('pythBar2').style.width=(c2*100)+'%';
  }
  sl.addEventListener('input',update);
  update();
})();
</script>
""";
    }
}

scene "quiz_pythagorean" {
    index: "a9";
    concept: "pythagorean";
    title: "Quiz: Pythagorean Identities";

    mcq "q_pyth1" {
        Q: "Simplify: sin²θ + cos²θ + tan²θ";
        A: "b";
        O: a) "1", b) "sec²θ", c) "tan²θ", d) "csc²θ";
        on_correct: {            feedback: "Excellent! sin²θ + cos²θ = 1, then 1 + tan²θ = sec²θ. Chain the identities!";
            goto "q_pyth2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Step 1: sin²θ + cos²θ = 1. Step 2: 1 + tan²θ = sec²θ. Two Pythagorean identities chained!";
            @loopback "pythagorean_identities" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_pyth2" {
        Q: "If cos θ = 5/13, what is sin²θ?";
        A: "c";
        O: a) "25/169", b) "12/13", c) "144/169", d) "169/144";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Right! sin²θ = 1 - cos²θ = 1 - 25/169 = 144/169.";
            goto "q_pyth3";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Use sin²θ = 1 - cos²θ = 1 - (5/13)² = 1 - 25/169 = 144/169.";
            @loopback "pythagorean_identities" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_pyth3" {
        Q: "What does (sec θ - tan θ)(sec θ + tan θ) simplify to?";
        A: "a";
        O: a) "1", b) "sec²θ", c) "tan²θ", d) "0";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Brilliant! This is (a-b)(a+b) = a²-b² = sec²θ - tan²θ = 1.";
            goto "quotient_cofunction";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Use difference of squares: sec²θ - tan²θ. From Pythagorean identity, this equals 1.";
            @loopback "pythagorean_identities" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 4: QUOTIENT & CO-FUNCTION (Formulas 13-20)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "quotient_cofunction" {
    index: "a10";    format: "markdown";
    concept: "quotient_cofunction";
    title: "6. Quotient & Co-function Identities (Formulas 13–20)";
    body: """
## Quotient Identities (Formulas 13–14)

\\[\\tan\\theta = \\frac{\\sin\\theta}{\\cos\\theta} \\quad \\text{(Formula 13)}\\]

\\[\\cot\\theta = \\frac{\\cos\\theta}{\\sin\\theta} \\quad \\text{(Formula 14)}\\]

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** Whenever you see a fraction with sin and cos, check if it simplifies to tan or cot. This is the single most common simplification in trig MCQs.

---

## Co-function Identities (Formulas 15–20)

These relate trig functions of **complementary angles** (angles that sum to 90°).

\\[\\sin(90° - \\theta) = \\cos\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 15)}\\]
\\[\\cos(90° - \\theta) = \\sin\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 16)}\\]
\\[\\tan(90° - \\theta) = \\cot\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 17)}\\]
\\[\\cot(90° - \\theta) = \\tan\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 18)}\\]
\\[\\sec(90° - \\theta) = \\csc\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 19)}\\]
\\[\\csc(90° - \\theta) = \\sec\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 20)}\\]

### The Pattern

Each function becomes its **co**-partner:
- sin ↔ cos
- tan ↔ cot
- sec ↔ csc

> **🏎️ Speed Trick:** If you see \\(\\sin 70°\\) and \\(\\cos 20°\\) in the same MCQ, they are **equal** (since 70 + 20 = 90). Use this to cancel terms or simplify expressions instantly.

### MCQ Example

**Q:** Simplify \\(\\sin 35° / \\cos 55°\\)

**Solution:** Since 35 + 55 = 90, we know \\(\\cos 55° = \\sin 35°\\). The answer is **1**.
""";
}

scene "quiz_quotient_cofunction" {
    index: "a11";
    concept: "quotient_cofunction";
    title: "Quiz: Quotient & Co-function";

    mcq "q_qc1" {
        Q: "Simplify: (sin θ / cos θ) × cos θ";
        A: "a";        O: a) "sin θ", b) "cos θ", c) "tan θ", d) "1";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Correct! sin θ/cos θ = tan θ, then tan θ × cos θ = sin θ. Or just cancel cos θ directly!";
            goto "q_qc2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "The cos θ in the denominator and numerator cancel, leaving just sin θ.";
            @loopback "quotient_cofunction" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_qc2" {
        Q: "What is sin 60° / cos 30°?";
        A: "c";
        O: a) "√3", b) "1/2", c) "1", d) "√3/2";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Perfect! Since 60 + 30 = 90, sin 60° = cos 30°, so the ratio is 1.";
            goto "even_odd";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Co-function: sin 60° = cos(90°-60°) = cos 30°. So sin 60° / cos 30° = 1.";
            @loopback "quotient_cofunction" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 5: EVEN-ODD IDENTITIES (Formulas 21-23)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "even_odd" {
    index: "a12";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "even_odd";
    title: "7. Even-Odd Identities (Formulas 21–23)";
    body: """
## Formulas 21–23: Even-Odd Properties

These tell you what happens when you **negate the angle**.

\\[\\sin(-\\theta) = -\\sin\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 21 — sin is ODD)}\\]

\\[\\cos(-\\theta) = \\cos\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 22 — cos is EVEN)}\\]

\\[\\tan(-\\theta) = -\\tan\\theta \\quad \\text{(Formula 23 — tan is ODD)}\\]
### Memory Rule

- **sin** and **tan** are **odd** functions → negative sign comes out
- **cos** is an **even** function → sign stays the same
- The reciprocals follow the same pattern: csc and cot are odd, sec is even

### Visual Intuition

On the unit circle, negating the angle reflects the point across the x-axis:
- The x-coordinate (cos) stays the same → even
- The y-coordinate (sin) flips sign → odd

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** When you see a negative angle in an MCQ, **pull the negative sign out immediately** for sin and tan, and **drop it** for cos. This takes 2 seconds and often reveals the answer.

### Example

**Q:** \\(\\cos(-45°) + \\sin(-45°)\\) = ?

**A:** \\(\\cos 45° - \\sin 45° = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} - \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} = 0\\)
""";
}

scene "quiz_even_odd" {
    index: "a13";
    concept: "even_odd";
    title: "Quiz: Even-Odd Identities";

    mcq "q_eo1" {
        Q: "What is sin(-30°)?";
        A: "b";
        O: a) "1/2", b) "-1/2", c) "√3/2", d) "-√3/2";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Right! sin is odd, so sin(-30°) = -sin(30°) = -1/2.";
            goto "q_eo2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "sin is an odd function: sin(-θ) = -sin(θ). So sin(-30°) = -sin(30°) = -1/2.";
            @loopback "even_odd" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_eo2" {
        Q: "Simplify: cos(-θ) + cos(θ)";
        A: "c";
        O: a) "0", b) "cos θ", c) "2cos θ", d) "2sin θ";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Correct! cos is even, so cos(-θ) = cos(θ). Thus cos(θ) + cos(θ) = 2cos θ.";
            goto "speed_tips_1";        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "cos is even: cos(-θ) = cos(θ). So the expression becomes cos θ + cos θ = 2cos θ.";
            @loopback "even_odd" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// SPEED TIPS INTERLUDE 1
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "speed_tips_1" {
    index: "a14";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "speed_tricks";
    title: "⚡ Speed Tips: Solving MCQs in Under 30 Seconds (Part 1)";
    body: """
## MCQ Speed Strategy #1: The Elimination Method

When you have less than 30 seconds, **don't solve — eliminate**.

### Trick 1: Plug in θ = 0° or θ = 90°

If the identity should hold for ALL θ, test with a simple angle:

**Example:** Which expression equals 1?
- A) sin²θ + cos²θ → sin²0 + cos²0 = 0 + 1 = **1** ✓
- B) sin²θ - cos²θ → 0 - 1 = -1 ✗
- C) sin θ + cos θ → 0 + 1 = 1 (but try θ=45°: √2/2 + √2/2 = √2 ≠ 1) ✗

> **This trick solves 60% of identity MCQs in under 10 seconds.**

### Trick 2: Check the Degree of the Expression

- If the question involves only sin²θ and cos²θ terms, think **Pythagorean**.
- If you see products like sin A cos B, think **Product-to-Sum**.
- If you see sin(A+B), think **Sum Formula** or expand immediately.

### Trick 3: Dimensional Analysis of Trig

Count the "degree" of trig functions:
- sin²θ cos²θ is degree 4
- If the answer choices have different degrees, you can often eliminate wrong ones

### Trick 4: The "Convert Everything to sin and cos" Rule

When stuck, convert ALL functions to sin and cos:- tan → sin/cos
- cot → cos/sin
- sec → 1/cos
- csc → 1/sin

Then simplify the algebra. This is a **universal fallback** that always works.
""";
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 6: SUM & DIFFERENCE FORMULAS (Formulas 24-29)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "sum_diff_formulas" {
    index: "a15";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "sum_difference";
    title: "8. Sum & Difference Formulas (Formulas 24–29)";
    body: """
## The Six Addition/Subtraction Formulas

These are essential for expanding compound angles and are the **foundation** for double angle and half angle formulas.

### Sine Formulas

\\[\\sin(A + B) = \\sin A \\cos B + \\cos A \\sin B \\quad \\text{(Formula 24)}\\]

\\[\\sin(A - B) = \\sin A \\cos B - \\cos A \\sin B \\quad \\text{(Formula 25)}\\]

> **Memory aid:** "Sine keeps the sign" — the sign between terms matches the sign between angles.

### Cosine Formulas

\\[\\cos(A + B) = \\cos A \\cos B - \\sin A \\sin B \\quad \\text{(Formula 26)}\\]

\\[\\cos(A - B) = \\cos A \\cos B + \\sin A \\sin B \\quad \\text{(Formula 27)}\\]

> **Memory aid:** "Cosine changes the sign" — the sign between terms is OPPOSITE to the sign between angles.

### Tangent Formulas

\\[\\tan(A + B) = \\frac{\\tan A + \\tan B}{1 - \\tan A \\tan B} \\quad \\text{(Formula 28)}\\]

\\[\\tan(A - B) = \\frac{\\tan A - \\tan B}{1 + \\tan A \\tan B} \\quad \\text{(Formula 29)}\\]

### Pattern Summary

| Function | Same sign in angle | Opposite sign in terms? |
|----------|-------------------|------------------------|
| sin      | Yes               | No (same sign)         || cos      | No                | Yes (opposite sign)    |
| tan      | Yes               | No (same sign in num)  |

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** If you see \\(\\sin 75°\\) in an MCQ, break it as \\(\\sin(45° + 30°)\\) and expand. Same for 15° = 45° - 30°, 105° = 60° + 45°, etc. **Know your angle decompositions!**
""";
}

scene "sum_diff_sim" {
    index: "a16";
    concept: "sum_difference";
    title: "Interactive: Sum & Difference Explorer";
    simulation "sum_diff_sim" {
        description: "Verify sin(A+B) = sinA cosB + cosA sinB by adjusting angles A and B.";
        raw: """
<div style="font-family:sans-serif;background:#0f0f23;color:#e0e0e0;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;">
  <h3 style="color:#4ecdc4;text-align:center;">sin(A+B) Formula Verifier</h3>
  <div style="display:flex;gap:20px;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;margin:15px 0;">
    <div>A: <input type="range" id="angleA" min="0" max="180" value="30" style="width:120px;"> <span id="valA">30</span>°</div>
    <div>B: <input type="range" id="angleB" min="0" max="180" value="45" style="width:120px;"> <span id="valB">45</span>°</div>
  </div>
  <div style="display:flex;justify-content:center;gap:20px;flex-wrap:wrap;">
    <div style="background:#1a1a3e;padding:15px;border-radius:8px;text-align:center;min-width:180px;">
      <div style="color:#ffe66d;font-weight:bold;">Direct</div>
      <div>sin(<span id="sumAngle">75</span>°)</div>
      <div style="font-size:22px;margin-top:5px;" id="directVal">0.9659</div>
    </div>
    <div style="background:#1a1a3e;padding:15px;border-radius:8px;text-align:center;min-width:180px;">
      <div style="color:#ff6b6b;font-weight:bold;">Formula</div>
      <div>sinA·cosB + cosA·sinB</div>
      <div style="font-size:22px;margin-top:5px;" id="formulaVal">0.9659</div>
    </div>
    <div style="background:#1a1a3e;padding:15px;border-radius:8px;text-align:center;min-width:120px;">
      <div style="color:#4ecdc4;font-weight:bold;">Match?</div>
      <div style="font-size:28px;margin-top:5px;" id="matchIcon">✅</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<script>
(function(){
  const sA=document.getElementById('angleA'),sB=document.getElementById('angleB');
  function update(){
    const a=parseFloat(sA.value),b=parseFloat(sB.value);
    const ar=a*Math.PI/180,br=b*Math.PI/180;
    document.getElementById('valA').textContent=a;
    document.getElementById('valB').textContent=b;
    document.getElementById('sumAngle').textContent=(a+b);
    const direct=Math.sin(ar+br);
    const formula=Math.sin(ar)*Math.cos(br)+Math.cos(ar)*Math.sin(br);
    document.getElementById('directVal').textContent=direct.toFixed(4);
    document.getElementById('formulaVal').textContent=formula.toFixed(4);    document.getElementById('matchIcon').textContent=Math.abs(direct-formula)<0.001?'✅':'❌';
  }
  sA.addEventListener('input',update);sB.addEventListener('input',update);update();
})();
</script>
""";
    }
}

scene "quiz_sum_diff" {
    index: "a17";
    concept: "sum_difference";
    title: "Quiz: Sum & Difference Formulas";

    mcq "q_sd1" {
        Q: "What is the exact value of sin 75°?";
        A: "b";
        O: a) "(√6 - √2)/4", b) "(√6 + √2)/4", c) "(√3 + 1)/4", d) "√3/2";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Excellent! sin(45°+30°) = sin45·cos30 + cos45·sin30 = (√2/2)(√3/2) + (√2/2)(1/2) = (√6+√2)/4.";
            goto "q_sd2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Write 75° = 45° + 30°. Expand: sin45·cos30 + cos45·sin30 = (√2/2)(√3/2) + (√2/2)(1/2) = (√6+√2)/4.";
            @loopback "sum_diff_formulas" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_sd2" {
        Q: "cos(A-B) - cos(A+B) simplifies to:";
        A: "d";
        O: a) "2cosA cosB", b) "-2sinA sinB", c) "2cosA sinB", d) "2sinA sinB";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Right! cos(A-B) = cosAcosB + sinAsinB and cos(A+B) = cosAcosB - sinAsinB. Subtracting gives 2sinAsinB.";
            goto "double_angle";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Expand both: cos(A-B) = cosAcosB+sinAsinB, cos(A+B) = cosAcosB-sinAsinB. Difference = 2sinAsinB.";
            @loopback "sum_diff_formulas" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 7: DOUBLE ANGLE FORMULAS (Formulas 30-32)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────
scene "double_angle" {
    index: "a18";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "double_angle";
    title: "9. Double Angle Formulas (Formulas 30–32)";
    body: """
## Derived from Sum Formulas by Setting A = B = θ

### Formula 30: sin 2θ

\\[\\sin 2\\theta = 2\\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta\\]

### Formula 31: cos 2θ (THREE FORMS!)

\\[\\cos 2\\theta = \\cos^2\\theta - \\sin^2\\theta \\quad \\text{(Form A)}\\]

Using \\(\\sin^2\\theta = 1 - \\cos^2\\theta\\):

\\[\\cos 2\\theta = 2\\cos^2\\theta - 1 \\quad \\text{(Form B)}\\]

Using \\(\\cos^2\\theta = 1 - \\sin^2\\theta\\):

\\[\\cos 2\\theta = 1 - 2\\sin^2\\theta \\quad \\text{(Form C)}\\]

### Formula 32: tan 2θ

\\[\\tan 2\\theta = \\frac{2\\tan\\theta}{1 - \\tan^2\\theta}\\]

### When to Use Which Form of cos 2θ?

| If you know... | Use Form |
|----------------|----------|
| Both sin θ and cos θ | A: cos²θ - sin²θ |
| Only cos θ | B: 2cos²θ - 1 |
| Only sin θ | C: 1 - 2sin²θ |

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** The identity \\(1 - 2\\sin^2\\theta = \\cos 2\\theta\\) and \\(2\\cos^2\\theta - 1 = \\cos 2\\theta\\) are **extremely common** in MCQs. If you see either pattern, replace immediately with cos 2θ.

> **🏎️ Speed Tip #2:** Similarly, \\(2\\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta\\) should **instantly** trigger sin 2θ in your mind. Don't leave it un-simplified.
""";
}

scene "quiz_double_angle" {
    index: "a19";
    concept: "double_angle";
    title: "Quiz: Double Angle Formulas";

    mcq "q_da1" {
        Q: "If sin θ = 3/5 and cos θ = 4/5, what is sin 2θ?";        A: "c";
        O: a) "7/25", b) "12/25", c) "24/25", d) "1";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Right! sin 2θ = 2 sinθ cosθ = 2(3/5)(4/5) = 24/25.";
            goto "q_da2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Use sin 2θ = 2 sinθ cosθ = 2 × (3/5) × (4/5) = 24/25.";
            @loopback "double_angle" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_da2" {
        Q: "Simplify: 1 - 2sin²(15°)";
        A: "b";
        O: a) "sin 30°", b) "cos 30°", c) "cos 15°", d) "sin 15°";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Perfect! This is the Form C pattern: 1 - 2sin²θ = cos 2θ. So cos(2×15°) = cos 30°.";
            goto "half_angle";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Recognize the pattern: 1 - 2sin²θ = cos 2θ. Here θ = 15°, so cos 30°.";
            @loopback "double_angle" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 8: HALF ANGLE FORMULAS (Formulas 33-35)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "half_angle" {
    index: "a20";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "half_angle";
    title: "10. Half Angle Formulas (Formulas 33–35)";
    body: """
## Derived from cos 2θ by Substituting θ → θ/2

### Formula 33: sin(θ/2)

\\[\\sin\\frac{\\theta}{2} = \\pm\\sqrt{\\frac{1 - \\cos\\theta}{2}}\\]

### Formula 34: cos(θ/2)

\\[\\cos\\frac{\\theta}{2} = \\pm\\sqrt{\\frac{1 + \\cos\\theta}{2}}\\]
### Formula 35: tan(θ/2)

\\[\\tan\\frac{\\theta}{2} = \\frac{\\sin\\theta}{1 + \\cos\\theta} = \\frac{1 - \\cos\\theta}{\\sin\\theta}\\]

### The Sign (±) Rule

The sign depends on which **quadrant** θ/2 falls in:
- Quadrant I: all positive
- Quadrant II: sin positive, cos negative
- Quadrant III: tan positive, sin and cos negative
- Quadrant IV: cos positive, sin negative

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** The tan half-angle formula has **no square root**, making it the fastest to compute. If you need tan(θ/2), always use Formula 35 instead of dividing sin(θ/2) by cos(θ/2).

> **🏎️ Speed Tip #2:** Half angle formulas are the key to finding exact values of unusual angles:
> - sin 15° = sin(30°/2)
> - cos 22.5° = cos(45°/2)
> - tan 75° = ... wait, that's not half. But tan 22.5° = tan(45°/2) ✓
""";
}

scene "quiz_half_angle" {
    index: "a21";
    concept: "half_angle";
    title: "Quiz: Half Angle Formulas";

    mcq "q_ha1" {
        Q: "Using the half angle formula, what is cos(45°/2)?";
        A: "a";
        O: a) "√(2+√2)/2", b) "√(2-√2)/2", c) "√2/2", d) "1/2";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Right! cos(θ/2) = √((1+cosθ)/2) = √((1+√2/2)/2) = √((2+√2)/4) = √(2+√2)/2.";
            goto "q_ha2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "cos(22.5°) = √((1+cos45°)/2) = √((1+√2/2)/2) = √(2+√2)/2.";
            @loopback "half_angle" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_ha2" {
        Q: "tan(θ/2) can be written WITHOUT a square root as:";
        A: "c";
        O: a) "(1+cosθ)/sinθ", b) "sinθ/(1-cosθ)", c) "sinθ/(1+cosθ)", d) "cosθ/(1+sinθ)";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Correct! tan(θ/2) = sinθ/(1+cosθ) is the radical-free form. Super useful for quick computation.";
            goto "product_sum";        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "The radical-free half angle for tangent: tan(θ/2) = sinθ/(1+cosθ).";
            @loopback "half_angle" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 9: PRODUCT-TO-SUM & SUM-TO-PRODUCT (Formulas 36-43)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "product_sum" {
    index: "a22";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "product_sum";
    title: "11. Product-to-Sum & Sum-to-Product (Formulas 36–43)";
    body: """
## Product-to-Sum Formulas (Formulas 36–39)

These convert **products** of trig functions into **sums/differences**.

\\[\\sin A \\sin B = \\frac{1}{2}[\\cos(A-B) - \\cos(A+B)] \\quad \\text{(36)}\\]

\\[\\cos A \\cos B = \\frac{1}{2}[\\cos(A-B) + \\cos(A+B)] \\quad \\text{(37)}\\]

\\[\\sin A \\cos B = \\frac{1}{2}[\\sin(A+B) + \\sin(A-B)] \\quad \\text{(38)}\\]

\\[\\cos A \\sin B = \\frac{1}{2}[\\sin(A+B) - \\sin(A-B)] \\quad \\text{(39)}\\]

### Memory Aid: "SS = -CC, CC = +CC, SC = +SS, CS = +SS"

- **S**in × **S**in → **C**os - **C**os (minus)
- **C**os × **C**os → **C**os + **C**os (plus)
- **S**in × **C**os → **S**in + **S**in
- **C**os × **S**in → **S**in - **S**in

---

## Sum-to-Product Formulas (Formulas 40–43)

These convert **sums/differences** into **products**.

\\[\\sin A + \\sin B = 2\\sin\\frac{A+B}{2}\\cos\\frac{A-B}{2} \\quad \\text{(40)}\\]

\\[\\sin A - \\sin B = 2\\cos\\frac{A+B}{2}\\sin\\frac{A-B}{2} \\quad \\text{(41)}\\]

\\[\\cos A + \\cos B = 2\\cos\\frac{A+B}{2}\\cos\\frac{A-B}{2} \\quad \\text{(42)}\\]
\\[\\cos A - \\cos B = -2\\sin\\frac{A+B}{2}\\sin\\frac{A-B}{2} \\quad \\text{(43)}\\]

### Memory Aid for Sum-to-Product

- **S**in ± **S**in → **S** × **C** (sin then cos)
- **C**os + **C**os → **C** × **C** (cos then cos)
- **C**os - **C**os → **-S** × **S** (negative, sin then sin)

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** These formulas are tested when you see expressions like "sin 50° + sin 10°" or "cos 75° × cos 15°". Recognize the pattern and convert immediately.

> **🏎️ Speed Tip #2:** For MCQs involving numerical values, Product-to-Sum often converts hard products into easy sums of known angles. E.g., cos 75° × cos 15° = ½[cos 60° + cos 90°] = ½[1/2 + 0] = **1/4**.
""";
}

scene "product_sum_sim" {
    index: "a23";
    concept: "product_sum";
    title: "Interactive: Product-to-Sum Verifier";
    simulation "ps_sim" {
        description: "Verify sin A × cos B = ½[sin(A+B) + sin(A-B)] interactively.";
        raw: """
<div style="font-family:sans-serif;background:#0f0f23;color:#e0e0e0;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;">
  <h3 style="color:#ffe66d;text-align:center;">sin A × cos B = ½[sin(A+B) + sin(A-B)]</h3>
  <div style="display:flex;gap:20px;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;margin:15px 0;">
    <div>A: <input type="range" id="psA" min="0" max="180" value="60"> <span id="psAv">60</span>°</div>
    <div>B: <input type="range" id="psB" min="0" max="180" value="30"> <span id="psBv">30</span>°</div>
  </div>
  <div style="display:flex;justify-content:center;gap:20px;flex-wrap:wrap;">
    <div style="background:#1a1a3e;padding:15px;border-radius:8px;text-align:center;">
      <div style="color:#ff6b6b;">Product</div>
      <div>sin A × cos B</div>
      <div style="font-size:22px;" id="psProduct">0.7500</div>
    </div>
    <div style="background:#1a1a3e;padding:15px;border-radius:8px;text-align:center;">
      <div style="color:#4ecdc4;">Sum Formula</div>
      <div>½[sin(A+B)+sin(A-B)]</div>
      <div style="font-size:22px;" id="psSum">0.7500</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<script>
(function(){
  const sA=document.getElementById('psA'),sB=document.getElementById('psB');
  function update(){
    const a=parseFloat(sA.value),b=parseFloat(sB.value);
    const ar=a*Math.PI/180,br=b*Math.PI/180;
    document.getElementById('psAv').textContent=a;
    document.getElementById('psBv').textContent=b;
    const prod=Math.sin(ar)*Math.cos(br);    const sum=0.5*(Math.sin(ar+br)+Math.sin(ar-br));
    document.getElementById('psProduct').textContent=prod.toFixed(4);
    document.getElementById('psSum').textContent=sum.toFixed(4);
  }
  sA.addEventListener('input',update);sB.addEventListener('input',update);update();
})();
</script>
""";
    }
}

scene "quiz_product_sum" {
    index: "a24";
