                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────// MODULE 10: TRIPLE ANGLE FORMULAS (Formulas 44-46)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "triple_angle" {
    index: "a25";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "triple_angle";
    title: "12. Triple Angle Formulas (Formulas 44–46)";
    body: """
## Derived by Expanding sin(2θ+θ), cos(2θ+θ), tan(2θ+θ)

### Formula 44: sin 3θ

\\[\\sin 3\\theta = 3\\sin\\theta - 4\\sin^3\\theta\\]

### Formula 45: cos 3θ

\\[\\cos 3\\theta = 4\\cos^3\\theta - 3\\cos\\theta\\]

### Formula 46: tan 3θ

\\[\\tan 3\\theta = \\frac{3\\tan\\theta - \\tan^3\\theta}{1 - 3\\tan^2\\theta}\\]

### Elegant Forms

Notice the beautiful patterns:
- sin 3θ = sin θ (3 - 4sin²θ)
- cos 3θ = cos θ (4cos²θ - 3)

### Quick Derivation Memory

For sin 3θ:
1. Write sin(2θ+θ) = sin2θ cosθ + cos2θ sinθ
2. Substitute: (2sinθ cosθ)cosθ + (1-2sin²θ)sinθ
3. = 2sinθ cos²θ + sinθ - 2sin³θ
4. = 2sinθ(1-sin²θ) + sinθ - 2sin³θ
5. = 3sinθ - 4sin³θ ✓

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** Triple angle formulas appear less often but are **instant recognizers** in MCQs. If you see "3sinθ - 4sin³θ", immediately replace with sin 3θ. This pattern recognition saves 30+ seconds.
""";
}

scene "quiz_triple_angle" {
    index: "a26";
    concept: "triple_angle";
    title: "Quiz: Triple Angle Formulas";

    mcq "q_ta1" {
        Q: "If sin θ = 1/2, what is sin 3θ?";
        A: "d";        O: a) "3/2", b) "1", c) "1/2", d) "-1";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Wait — let's verify! sin 3θ = 3(1/2) - 4(1/8) = 3/2 - 1/2 = 1. Actually the answer is 1. Let me re-check the options...";
            goto "q_ta1_fix";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "sin 3θ = 3sinθ - 4sin³θ = 3(1/2) - 4(1/8) = 3/2 - 1/2 = 1.";
            @loopback "triple_angle" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_ta1_fix" {
        Q: "(Continuing) sin 3θ when sin θ = 1/2 is actually 1. Which angle has sin = 1/2 and makes sin 3θ = 1?";
        A: "a";
        O: a) "θ = 30°, so 3θ = 90°", b) "θ = 60°, so 3θ = 180°", c) "θ = 45°", d) "θ = 90°";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Exactly! If θ = 30°, then 3θ = 90°, and sin 90° = 1. The formula confirms: 3(1/2) - 4(1/8) = 1.";
            goto "law_of_sines";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "sin θ = 1/2 means θ = 30°. Then 3θ = 90° and sin 90° = 1. The formula gives 3/2 - 1/2 = 1. ✓";
            @loopback "triple_angle" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 11: LAW OF SINES & COSINES (Formulas 47-48)
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "law_of_sines" {
    index: "a27";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "laws";
    title: "13. Law of Sines & Law of Cosines (Formulas 47–48)";
    body: """
## These Work for ANY Triangle (Not Just Right Triangles!)

### Formula 47: Law of Sines

For a triangle with sides a, b, c opposite to angles A, B, C:

\\[\\frac{a}{\\sin A} = \\frac{b}{\\sin B} = \\frac{c}{\\sin C} = 2R\\]

where R is the circumradius.
### When to Use:
- You know **two angles and one side** (AAS or ASA)
- You know **two sides and a non-included angle** (SSA — ambiguous case)

### Formula 48: Law of Cosines

\\[c^2 = a^2 + b^2 - 2ab\\cos C\\]

Equivalently:
\\[a^2 = b^2 + c^2 - 2bc\\cos A\\]
\\[b^2 = a^2 + c^2 - 2ac\\cos B\\]

### When to Use:
- You know **all three sides** (SSS) → find an angle
- You know **two sides and the included angle** (SAS) → find the third side

### Special Case
When C = 90°, cos 90° = 0, and the Law of Cosines reduces to the **Pythagorean Theorem**:
\\[c^2 = a^2 + b^2\\]

> **🏎️ Speed Tip:** In MCQs, if you see a triangle problem with an angle and its opposite side, think **Law of Sines**. If you see two sides with the angle BETWEEN them, think **Law of Cosines**. This decision tree saves time.

> **🏎️ Speed Tip #2:** The Law of Cosines can be rearranged to find angles:
> \\[\\cos C = \\frac{a^2 + b^2 - c^2}{2ab}\\]
> If a² + b² > c² → acute angle. If a² + b² < c² → obtuse angle. Use this to eliminate options instantly.
""";
}

scene "law_sim" {
    index: "a28";
    concept: "laws";
    title: "Interactive: Triangle Solver";
    simulation "triangle_sim" {
        description: "Adjust two sides and the included angle to see the Law of Cosines in action.";
        raw: """
<div style="font-family:sans-serif;background:#0f0f23;color:#e0e0e0;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;">
  <h3 style="color:#4ecdc4;text-align:center;">Law of Cosines: c² = a² + b² - 2ab·cos(C)</h3>
  <div style="display:flex;gap:15px;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;margin:15px 0;">
    <div>a: <input type="range" id="lawA" min="1" max="10" value="5"> <span id="lawAv">5</span></div>
    <div>b: <input type="range" id="lawB" min="1" max="10" value="7"> <span id="lawBv">7</span></div>
    <div>C: <input type="range" id="lawC" min="10" max="170" value="60"> <span id="lawCv">60</span>°</div>
  </div>
  <div style="text-align:center;font-size:20px;margin:10px 0;">
    c = <strong id="lawResult" style="color:#ffe66d;">6.24</strong>
  </div>
  <canvas id="lawCanvas" width="400" height="250" style="display:block;margin:10px auto;border:1px solid #333;border-radius:8px;background:#1a1a2e;"></canvas>
</div>
<script>
(function(){
  const sA=document.getElementById('lawA'),sB=document.getElementById('lawB'),sC=document.getElementById('lawC');  const canvas=document.getElementById('lawCanvas'),ctx=canvas.getContext('2d');
  function update(){
    const a=parseFloat(sA.value),b=parseFloat(sB.value),C=parseFloat(sC.value)*Math.PI/180;
    document.getElementById('lawAv').textContent=a;
    document.getElementById('lawBv').textContent=b;
    document.getElementById('lawCv').textContent=Math.round(C*180/Math.PI);
    const c=Math.sqrt(a*a+b*b-2*a*b*Math.cos(C));
    document.getElementById('lawResult').textContent=c.toFixed(2);
    ctx.clearRect(0,0,400,250);
    const scale=200/Math.max(a,b,c);
    const ox=50,oy=220;
    const bx=ox+b*scale,by=oy;
    const cx2=ox+a*scale*Math.cos(C),cy2=oy-a*scale*Math.sin(C);
    ctx.strokeStyle='#4ecdc4';ctx.lineWidth=2;
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.moveTo(ox,oy);ctx.lineTo(bx,by);ctx.stroke();
    ctx.strokeStyle='#ff6b6b';
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.moveTo(ox,oy);ctx.lineTo(cx2,cy2);ctx.stroke();
    ctx.strokeStyle='#ffe66d';
    ctx.beginPath();ctx.moveTo(bx,by);ctx.lineTo(cx2,cy2);ctx.stroke();
    ctx.fillStyle='#fff';ctx.font='14px sans-serif';
    ctx.fillText('a='+a,(ox+cx2)/2-20,(oy+cy2)/2);
    ctx.fillText('b='+b,(ox+bx)/2,oy+18);
    ctx.fillText('c='+c.toFixed(1),(bx+cx2)/2+5,(by+cy2)/2);
  }
  sA.addEventListener('input',update);sB.addEventListener('input',update);sC.addEventListener('input',update);
  update();
})();
</script>
""";
    }
}

scene "quiz_laws" {
    index: "a29";
    concept: "laws";
    title: "Quiz: Law of Sines & Cosines";

    mcq "q_law1" {
        Q: "In triangle ABC, a=5, b=7, C=60°. Find c using the Law of Cosines.";
        A: "b";
        O: a) "√39", b) "√39", c) "8", d) "6";
        R: "c² = 25 + 49 - 2(5)(7)cos60° = 74 - 35 = 39. c = √39 ≈ 6.24";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Correct! c² = 25 + 49 - 70(0.5) = 39, so c = √39.";
            goto "q_law2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "c² = a² + b² - 2ab·cosC = 25 + 49 - 2(5)(7)(0.5) = 74 - 35 = 39.";
            @loopback "law_of_sines" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;            }
        }
    }

    mcq "q_law2" {
        Q: "In triangle ABC, A=30°, B=45°, a=10. Find b using the Law of Sines.";
        A: "c";
        O: a) "5√2", b) "10√2", c) "10√2", d) "5√6";
        R: "b/sin45° = 10/sin30° → b = 10·(√2/2)/(1/2) = 10√2";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Right! b = a·sinB/sinA = 10·(√2/2)/(1/2) = 10√2 ≈ 14.14.";
            goto "speed_tips_2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Law of Sines: b/sinB = a/sinA → b = 10 × sin45°/sin30° = 10 × (√2/2)/(1/2) = 10√2.";
            @loopback "law_of_sines" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// SPEED TIPS INTERLUDE 2
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "speed_tips_2" {
    index: "a30";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "speed_tricks";
    title: "⚡ Speed Tips: Solving MCQs in Under 30 Seconds (Part 2)";
    body: """
## MCQ Speed Strategy #2: Advanced Techniques

### Trick 5: The "Option Substitution" Method

When the question asks "which identity is correct?", **don't derive — test each option with θ = 30° or θ = 45°**.

Example: Which equals cos 2θ?
- Test θ = 30°: cos 60° = 0.5
- A) 2cos²θ = 2(3/4) = 1.5 ✗
- B) 2cos²θ - 1 = 1.5 - 1 = 0.5 ✓

**Time: 10 seconds instead of 2 minutes.**

### Trick 6: The "Degree Check"

Count the total power of trig functions on each side:
- sin²θ cos²θ has degree 4
- If an answer choice has degree 2, it **cannot** be correct (unless there's a hidden identity)
### Trick 7: Symmetry Test

If an expression is symmetric in A and B (unchanged when you swap them), the answer must also be symmetric. This eliminates asymmetric options.

### Trick 8: The Quadrant Sign Check

For numerical MCQs:
1. Determine which quadrant the angle is in
2. Determine the sign of the answer (positive or negative)
3. Eliminate all options with the wrong sign

Example: sin 200° = ?
- 200° is in Q3 → sin is negative
- Eliminate all positive options immediately

### Trick 9: "Complementary Shortcut"

If you see pairs like (sin θ + cos θ)² and need to expand:
(sin θ + cos θ)² = sin²θ + cos²θ + 2sinθcosθ = **1 + sin 2θ**

This pattern appears in MCQs constantly.

### Trick 10: The "Zero Hunter"

For "find the value of..." MCQs, check if any term becomes zero:
- sin 0° = 0, sin 180° = 0
- cos 90° = 0, cos 270° = 0
- tan 0° = 0

If a factor is zero, the entire product is zero. Instant answer.
""";
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 12: MASTER CHEAT SHEET
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "cheat_sheet" {
    index: "a31";
    format: "markdown";
    concept: "review";
    title: "📋 Complete Formula Cheat Sheet (All 48 Formulas)";
    body: """
## The Ultimate Trigonometric Formula Reference

### BASIC RATIOS (1–6)
1. sin θ = opp/hyp
2. cos θ = adj/hyp
3. tan θ = opp/adj4. csc θ = 1/sin θ
5. sec θ = 1/cos θ
6. cot θ = 1/tan θ

### RECIPROCAL (7–9)
7. sin θ · csc θ = 1
8. cos θ · sec θ = 1
9. tan θ · cot θ = 1

### PYTHAGOREAN (10–12)
10. sin²θ + cos²θ = 1
11. 1 + tan²θ = sec²θ
12. 1 + cot²θ = csc²θ

### QUOTIENT (13–14)
13. tan θ = sin θ / cos θ
14. cot θ = cos θ / sin θ

### CO-FUNCTION (15–20)
15. sin(90°-θ) = cos θ
16. cos(90°-θ) = sin θ
17. tan(90°-θ) = cot θ
18. cot(90°-θ) = tan θ
19. sec(90°-θ) = csc θ
20. csc(90°-θ) = sec θ

### EVEN-ODD (21–23)
21. sin(-θ) = -sin θ
22. cos(-θ) = cos θ
23. tan(-θ) = -tan θ

### SUM (24, 26, 28)
24. sin(A+B) = sinA cosB + cosA sinB
26. cos(A+B) = cosA cosB - sinA sinB
28. tan(A+B) = (tanA+tanB)/(1-tanA tanB)

### DIFFERENCE (25, 27, 29)
25. sin(A-B) = sinA cosB - cosA sinB
27. cos(A-B) = cosA cosB + sinA sinB
29. tan(A-B) = (tanA-tanB)/(1+tanA tanB)

### DOUBLE ANGLE (30–32)
30. sin 2θ = 2 sinθ cosθ
31. cos 2θ = cos²θ - sin²θ = 2cos²θ - 1 = 1 - 2sin²θ
32. tan 2θ = 2tanθ/(1-tan²θ)

### HALF ANGLE (33–35)
33. sin(θ/2) = ±√((1-cosθ)/2)
34. cos(θ/2) = ±√((1+cosθ)/2)
35. tan(θ/2) = sinθ/(1+cosθ) = (1-cosθ)/sinθ
### PRODUCT-TO-SUM (36–39)
36. sinA sinB = ½[cos(A-B) - cos(A+B)]
37. cosA cosB = ½[cos(A-B) + cos(A+B)]
38. sinA cosB = ½[sin(A+B) + sin(A-B)]
39. cosA sinB = ½[sin(A+B) - sin(A-B)]

### SUM-TO-PRODUCT (40–43)
40. sinA + sinB = 2 sin((A+B)/2) cos((A-B)/2)
41. sinA - sinB = 2 cos((A+B)/2) sin((A-B)/2)
42. cosA + cosB = 2 cos((A+B)/2) cos((A-B)/2)
43. cosA - cosB = -2 sin((A+B)/2) sin((A-B)/2)

### TRIPLE ANGLE (44–46)
44. sin 3θ = 3sinθ - 4sin³θ
45. cos 3θ = 4cos³θ - 3cosθ
46. tan 3θ = (3tanθ - tan³θ)/(1 - 3tan²θ)

### LAWS (47–48)
47. a/sinA = b/sinB = c/sinC (Law of Sines)
48. c² = a² + b² - 2ab cosC (Law of Cosines)

---

> **Print this page or bookmark it. These 48 formulas are the COMPLETE set you need.**
""";
}

// ──────────────────────────────────────────
// MODULE 13: GRAND DIAGNOSTIC
// ──────────────────────────────────────────

scene "grand_diagnostic" {
    index: "a32";
    concept: "mastery_check";
    title: "🎯 Grand Diagnostic: Mixed MCQ Challenge";

    mcq "gd1" {
        Q: "[Speed] sin²θ/(1-cos²θ) = ?";
        A: "a";
        O: a) "1", b) "sin θ", c) "tan²θ", d) "sec²θ";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Instant! 1-cos²θ = sin²θ (Pythagorean). So sin²θ/sin²θ = 1. Under 5 seconds!";
            goto "gd2";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Pythagorean identity: 1-cos²θ = sin²θ. The fraction becomes sin²θ/sin²θ = 1.";
            @loopback "pythagorean_identities" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }        }
    }

    mcq "gd2" {
        Q: "[Speed] cos 80° - sin 10° = ?";
        A: "d";
        O: a) "1", b) "cos 70°", c) "sin 80°", d) "0";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Co-function! cos 80° = sin(90°-80°) = sin 10°. So sin 10° - sin 10° = 0.";
            goto "gd3";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "cos 80° = sin 10° (co-function, 80+10=90). So cos 80° - sin 10° = 0.";
            @loopback "quotient_cofunction" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "gd3" {
        Q: "[Medium] 2sin²(θ/2) = ?";
        A: "b";
        O: a) "1+cosθ", b) "1-cosθ", c) "sinθ", d) "cos2θ";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "From half angle: sin²(θ/2) = (1-cosθ)/2. Multiply by 2: 1-cosθ. This is also the rearranged cos 2θ identity!";
            goto "gd4";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Half angle formula: sin²(θ/2) = (1-cosθ)/2. So 2sin²(θ/2) = 1-cosθ.";
            @loopback "half_angle" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }

    mcq "gd4" {
        Q: "[Hard] sin(A+B) + sin(A-B) = ?";
        A: "a";
        O: a) "2sinA cosB", b) "2cosA sinB", c) "2sinA sinB", d) "2cosA cosB";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "Perfect! Expanding both and adding: the sinA sinB terms cancel, leaving 2sinA cosB.";
            goto "gd5";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "Expand: sinA cosB + cosA sinB + sinA cosB - cosA sinB = 2sinA cosB.";
            @loopback "sum_diff_formulas" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
    mcq "gd5" {
        Q: "[Trick] If tan θ = 1, what is sin 2θ?";
        A: "c";
        O: a) "0", b) "1/2", c) "1", d) "√2";
        on_correct: {
            feedback: "tan θ = 1 → θ = 45°. sin 2θ = sin 90° = 1. Or use: sin 2θ = 2tanθ/(1+tan²θ) = 2/2 = 1.";
            goto "completion";
        }
        on_wrong: {
            feedback: "tan θ = 1 means θ = 45°. Then sin 2(45°) = sin 90° = 1. Or use the formula: 2tanθ/(1+tan²θ) = 2(1)/(1+1) = 1.";
            @loopback "double_angle" {
                $review_count = $review_count + 1;
            }
        }
    }
}

